{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Plotting pupillometric data for exploration\n",
    "\n",
    "It is crucial to validate preprocessing steps by visually inspecting the results using plots. Therefore, `pypillometry` implements several plotting facilities that encourage active exploration of the dataset. Some of the plotting functions require a Jupyter-notebook with enable widgets (see Installation instructions) so that the plots can be changed interactively, others are purely `matplotlib`-based."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 62,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import sys\n",
    "sys.path.insert(0,\"..\")\n",
    "import pypillometry as pp\n",
    "import pylab as plt ## access matplotlib functions\n",
    "\n",
    "d=pp.PupilData.from_file(\"../data/test.pd\")\n",
    "faked=pp.create_fake_pupildata(ntrials=20)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Each `PupilData` object has a default `plot()` function that, by default, plots the complete signal at once. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))\n",
    "d.plot()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Often, the signal is too long to fit comfortably into one plot, therefore plot allows to specify a range by specifying the `plot_range=` argument with a `tuple` giving start end end of the plot. For longer recordings, it can be useful to specify the range in different time units by using `units=`. `pypillometry` supports `ms` (milliseconds), `sec` (seconds), `min` (minutes) and `h` (hours)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x360 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))\n",
    "plt.subplot(1,2,1)\n",
    "d.plot((260, 280), units=\"sec\")\n",
    "plt.subplot(1,2,2)\n",
    "d.plot((4.5, 4.7), units=\"min\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that the scale of the plots went all the way to zero because missing data is represented by `0` in the used eyetracker. \n",
    "\n",
    "When we detect and interpolate blinks (see [blinks-notebook](blinks.html)), the scale is adjusted and detected blinks highlighted in red."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x360 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "## detect and interpolate blinks\n",
    "d=d.blinks_detect()\n",
    "d2=d.blinks_interp_mahot()\n",
    "\n",
    "## plot results\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))\n",
    "plt.subplot(1,2,1)\n",
    "d.plot((260, 280), units=\"sec\")\n",
    "plt.subplot(1,2,2)\n",
    "d2.plot((260, 280), units=\"sec\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In order to enable interactive plotting, you can either use widget-based plotting in the jupyter notebook by using `interactive=True`, or pop-out the plot in `matplotlib`'s plotting window which allows zooming, moving etc. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json": {
       "model_id": "966a6639c256407b8b3b3712b170391a",
       "version_major": 2,
       "version_minor": 0
      },
      "text/plain": [
       "interactive(children=(FloatRangeSlider(value=(240.0, 360.0), continuous_update=False, description=' ', layout=…"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "## produces plot with adjustable x-axis for exploring signal\n",
    "d.plot(interactive=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Using matplotlib backend: MacOSX\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "## pops out the plot in matplotlibs native plotting window\n",
    "%matplotlib \n",
    "d.plot()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## reset to inline-plotting\n",
    "%matplotlib inline"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In case you are interested in modeling the signal (see notebook [modeling pupillometric signal](modeling.html)), the `plot()` function allows to plot the different components (baseline and response-model) as well as the full model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Furthermore, it is also possible to plot several datasets simultaneously using the module-level function `plotpd()`. \n",
    "\n",
    "By default, the signals are plotted into the same figure in different colors:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 71,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "pp.plotpd(d, d2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "By giving the additional argument `subplots=True`, we can also plot them separately as above:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 72,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "pp.plotpd(d, d2, subplots=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There is also an interactive version `plotpd_ia()` that produces a figure where the x-axis can be adjusted dynamically."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 73,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json": {
       "model_id": "fb812e74a6bd4c93ae9e44ec3bc8f28b",
       "version_major": 2,
       "version_minor": 0
      },
      "text/plain": [
       "interactive(children=(FloatRangeSlider(value=(240000.0, 360000.0), continuous_update=False, description=' ', l…"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "pp.plotpd_ia(d, d2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## `plot_segments()`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It is usally a good idea to browse through the whole pupillometric data before and after preprocessing. This can be useful for tweaking preprocessing parameters or for detecting gross artifacts. `pypillometry` offers a function `plot_segments()`, that produces as many plots as necessary (each displaying part of the data). \n",
    "\n",
    "The default is to return a list of `matplotlib`-Figure objects that can then manually be plotted/inspected. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "figs=d.plot_segments()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for fig in figs:\n",
    "    display(fig)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The function also allows to specify a (multi-page) PDF-file to which the plots will be saved for later inspection:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "> Writing PDF file '/tmp/test.pdf'\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "d.plot_segments(pdffile=\"/tmp/test.pdf\");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Another useful feature of this function is to compare the signals before and after preprocessing using the `overlay=` argument:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 47,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "figs=d.plot_segments(overlay=d2)\n",
    "display(figs[0])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## `blinks_plot()`\n",
    "\n",
    "Blinks can be tricky to interpolate. To facilite the process, `pypillometry` includes a function to plot all detected blinks. The function works similar to `plot_segments()`, i.e., it returns a list of Figure-objects or allows saving to a PDF file. Each plot contains the index of the currently displayed blink which allows to identify and locate individual blinks in the full dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 59,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "[<Figure size 720x720 with 28 Axes>]"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 59,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x720 with 28 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "d.blinks_plot(nrow=7, ncol=4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A special diagnostic plotting option for blinks is available in the `blinks_interp_mahot()` function. When called with the argument `plot=True`, it will produce plots similar to `blinks_plot()` but including information used by the Mahot-algorithm implemented in this function (see API docs for details)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 58,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x576 with 53 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "d.blinks_interp_mahot(plot=True, plot_dim=(7,4));"
   ]
  }
 ],
